Here's your chance to win 7 Day (6 nights) on @azaleacruise Azalea Yacht Cruise in the Maldives 🌴🌞 

Easy Steps To Win:

1) Click the link in @oceanfanaticsmaldives’s bio to enter!

2) Follow all 26 accounts that @oceanfanaticsmaldives follows.

Tag a friend (no spam)

Voucher would be valid from the date of announcement till 2023.

The winner will be chosen randomly on August 1st 2021 & announced on @azaleacruise account live & added to the caption of this post.

All included 7 days Maldives yacht trip. The winner selected cannot sell the voucher or give it away. Only the person who won (plus one) can claim the prize.
📷 @jalilnajafov 

Please Note: This sweepstake is in no way sponsored, administered, or associated with Instagram! By entering, entrants confirm they are 18+ years of age, release Instagram of responsibility, and agree to our term of use. (International flights are not included)

node.text:
Me during the heatwave in the U.K. this week. 😂
Video by @harnaswildlifefoundation
Explore. Share. Inspire: #earthfocus

Marine life deserves better ⚠️
A red tide has invaded the Gulf Coast of Florida, already killing more than 613 tons of marine life and fish in and around Tampa as of the past week, according to local officials.

Video & photos by @paulcuffaro

He documented this tragedy, saying: “EVERYTHING was dead, from bait fish to baby manatees. The red tide is a sudden overgrowth of Karenia brevis, rust-colored algae that secrete a deadly toxin, but over the years it’s progressed. This type of outcome most definitely could’ve been prevented. This is not a natural occurrence it’s negligence from the people in power.”

Scientists feared a large bloom was imminent after polluted wastewater from an abandoned phosphate mine at Piney Point was recently pumped into Tampa Bay to stop a leak from flooding surrounding neighborhoods and the elevated concentrations of nitrogen and phosphorus are known to fuel phytoplankton growth which can lead to a potentially toxic algal bloom.
Via @savethereef

node.text:
Western bush viper. Make sure you don’t miss the cute eye movement at the very end!

Video by @severus_snakes 🐍

It’s full name is “Atheris Chlorechis”
This species has been known to prey upon a variety of small amphibians, lizards, rodents, birds, and even other snakes. Some species or populations favor eating frogs, but most have been described as opportunistic feeders. Prey is typically ambushed from a hanging position, held until it has succumbed to the venom and then swallowed.
Not much is known about their venom except that it is strongly hemotoxic, causing pain, swelling and blood clotting problems. Until recently, their venom has often been regarded as less toxic than that of many other species, perhaps because bites are uncommon, but this turned out not to be the case. There are now a number of reports of bites that have led to severe hemorrhaging. One case was fatal. Atheris-specific antivenom does not exist and antivenom meant for bites from other species seem to have little effect, although Echis antivenom has been reported to have been of some help in a case.

Thanks for sharing @severus_snakes
